<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Review_the_deployment_summary">Review the deployment summary</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=T-1" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor" title="Edit section: ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;action=edit&amp;section=T-1" title="Edit section: ">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>On the <b>Summary</b> page, review the deployment information, and then click <b>NEXT</b>.  
</p><p><br>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Accept_the_license_agreement">Accept the license agreement</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=T-2" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor" title="Edit section: ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;action=edit&amp;section=T-2" title="Edit section: ">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>On the <b>End User License Agreement</b> page, accept the license agreements and data policy, and then click <b>NEXT</b>.  
</p><p><br>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Select_the_capabilities">Select the capabilities</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=T-3" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor" title="Edit section: ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;action=edit&amp;section=T-3" title="Edit section: ">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ol>
<li>On the <b>Capabilities</b> page, select the capabilities for the suite. The installer will download only those container images that are required for the selection that you make.

Note that no capability options may be displayed if the suite .json file only specifies one size. 
</li>
<li>Click <b>NEXT</b>. 
</li>
</ol>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Select_the_capabilities_2">Select the capabilities</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=Operations_Bridge:2019.05/SelectDeployConfigAWS&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=1" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor" title="Edit section: Select the capabilities">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=Operations_Bridge:2019.05/SelectDeployConfigAWS&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Select the capabilities">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ol><li>Select the edition you want to install. There are two editions available for install:
<ul><li>Premium: Operation Bridge Premium Edition is a suite that provides entitlement to multiple product components along with their associated license keys. These product components are represented as separate entitlements, listed below. The primary suite product does not provide a single license key. Note that different suite licenses are available that contain 5 or 50 packs. These packs define how many nodes you have available per product component.
<ul><li>Operations Manager i Event Management Foundation</li>
<li>Monitoring Automation for Composite Applications</li>
<li>Operations Bridge Reporter</li>
<li>Business Value Dashboard</li></ul></li></ul>
Additionally, CO monitoring-only is included with Operations&nbsp;Bridge Premium. You can open a CO monitoring-only case under Infra SPI (VISPI) or Infra MP.
<ul><li>Ultimate: Operation Bridge Ultimate Edition is a suite that provides entitlement to multiple product components along with their associated license keys. These product components are represented as separate entitlements, listed below. The primary suite product does not provide a single license key. Note that different suite licenses are available that contain 5 oder 50 packs. These packs define how many nodes you have available per product component.
<ul><li>Operations Manager i Event Management Foundation</li>
<li>Monitoring Automation for Composite Applications</li>
<li>Operations Bridge Reporter</li>
<li>Operations Orchestration</li>
<li>Operations Bridge Topology Based Event Correlation</li>
<li>Operations Bridge Analytics</li>
<li>Business Value Dashboard</li>
<li>Cloud Optimizer</li>
<li>Universal Discovery</li>
<li>Virtualization Collector</li>
<li>Performance Management</li>
<li>End-User Management</li></ul></li></ul>
</li><li>On the&nbsp;Capabilities&nbsp;page, select the capabilities for the suite. The installer will download only those container images that are required for the selection that you make. <br>
When installing the&nbsp;Operations Bridge Suite&nbsp;Premium, you can select the following capabilities:
<ul><li>Operations Bridge Manager: Operations Bridge Manager (OBM, formerly OMi) provides the ability to sense, analyze and adapt to manage IT services that support digital business. With advanced event correlation, log intelligence, predictive analytics and automation you can remediate issues across all your technologies to prioritize business targets.</li>
<li>Business Value Dashboard: Business Value Dashboards bring your data to life. Create custom, flexible dashboards that visualize information from different sources in an informative and appealing way. In contrast to the more operational monitoring dashboards, which are used to efficiently monitor system health, business value dashboards help you understand the value driven by your IT environment. Your dashboards can be accessed anywhere, anytime, from any device.</li>
<li>ITOM Intelligent Data Lake: ITOM Intelligent Data Lake is an ITOM platform component that brings in the data collection (Collect Once) and storage (Store Once) together which can receive and process high volume and velocity data from several independent data sources.</li>
<li>Virtualization Collector: Virtualization Collector is an OpsBridge capability which collects topology, metrics and events from the VMware Virtualization Infrastructure.</li>
<li>Performance Management&nbsp;Performance Management is an OpsBridge capability which pro-actively reports performance bottlenecks.</li>
<li>End User Management: EUM is an OpsBridge capability that enables you to proactively monitor network and application performance and availability in real time environment. You can use EUM to monitor and view the reports based on application and performance data.</li></ul>
</li><li>Click <b>NEXT</b>.</li></ol>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Select_the_CDF_database">Select the CDF database</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=T-4" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor" title="Edit section: ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;action=edit&amp;section=T-4" title="Edit section: ">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>On the <b>Database</b> page, select one of the following options to configure a database. If you select a PostgreSQL or Oracle database, make sure that the database is empty (has no objects)  before you begin the installation. 
</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Out-of-the-box PostgreSQL:</b> Select this option if you want to configure an embedded database.</li>
To enable high availability for the database, select <b>PostgreSQL High Availability</b> (however, we do not recommend that you do this in single master node environments). 
<li><b>PostgreSQL:</b> Select this option if you are connecting to a PostgreSQL database that you are providing or managing on another server. Provide the following details of the IdM database. Make sure you are providing a PostgreSQL database with non-public a schema.</li>
If your database requires Secure Sockets Layer (SSL), select <b>Use SSL connection</b>, and then click <b>Upload</b> to upload your database server certificate in .pem format.<br>
<br> 
<ul>
<li>If you uncheck the <b>If no database is found, create a database automatically</b> option, you must create an IdM database with non-public schema and a database user in advance. See the details in the external database preparation page under the <b>Prepare</b> section. <br>
Provide the following details of the IdM database.<br>
<ul><li>Enter the <b>Database Host</b> and <b>Port</b>.<br></li>
<li>Enter the <b>Database name</b> which is the value you set for &lt;cdfidmdb&gt; while creating the external database. <br></li>
<li>Enter database user as the  <b>User</b> which is the value you set for &lt;cdfidmuser&gt; while creating the external database</li>
<li>Enter the corresponding database <b>Password</b> details.</li></ul>
The user you provided will be used to connect the IdM database. <br>
<br>
</li>
<li>If you have not yet created a database, select the <b>If no database is found, create a database automatically</b> option.  Due to lack of  the "Superuser" role on AWS RDS, this option is not supported for AWS RDS.<br>
Provide the following details of the IdM database.<br>
<ul><li>Enter the <b>Database Host</b> and <b>Port</b>.<br></li>
<li>Enter the <b>Database name</b>.<br></li>
<li>Enter a PostgreSQL admin user as the  <b>User</b>, and corresponding <b>Password</b> details. Make sure the admin user has the "Superuser" role. <br></li></ul>
For example: enter the following information for the PostgreSQL database:<br>
<pre>Host:db1.myhost.com
Port:5432
Database name:cdfidm
User:postgres_admin
Password:****
</pre>
<p>The installer will automatically create an empty database using the database information you provided. The installer will also create a "cdfidm" user and set the "cdfidm" user as the database owner. <br> 
</p>
</li>
</ul>
<li><b>Oracle:</b> Select this option to connect to an Oracle database that you are providing or managing on another server. You need to create an IdM database user in advance. <br>
Provide the following details of the IdM database.</li>
<ol>
<li>Select a <b>Connection type</b>, and then enter the following information:</li>
<ul>
<li>For the SID type: Enter the <b>Database host</b>, <b>Port number</b>, <b>SID</b>, <b>Schema</b>, <b>User</b>, and <b>Password</b>.<br>
For example: enter the following information for the Oracle database.<br>
<pre>Host: db1.myhost.com
Port: 1521
SID: orcl
Schema: cdfidm
User:cdfidm
</pre>
</li>
<li>For the Connection String type: Enter the <b>Connection string</b>, <b>Schema</b>, <b>User</b>, and <b>Password</b>.<br>
For example: enter the following information for the Oracle database.<br>
<pre>Host: db1.myhost.com
Port: 1521
Connection String:(DESCRIPTION =(LOAD_BALANCE=on)
    (ADDRESS = (PROTOCOL = TCP)(HOST = orcl1.test.com)(PORT = 1521))
    (CONNECT_DATA =
      (SERVER = DEDICATED)
      (SID = orcl)
    )
  )
Schema: cdfidm
User:cdfidm
Password:******
</pre>
</li>
</ul>
<li>Click <b>Select JDBC driver(s)</b> to select JDBC driver file(s). Wait until all the JDBC driver file(s) have been uploaded successfully. Then click <b>UPLOAD</b> to upload an Oracle JDBC driver file for your database.  If you want to upload multiple JDBC driver files, select all driver files at one time and then click <b>UPLOAD</b>. To replace the existing JDBC driver files, upload the new driver files before you set up the database. The latest uploaded driver files replace the driver files you uploaded previously. You only need to upload one JDBC driver file. For example, ojdbc*.jar. If you want to upload multiple JDBC driver files, contact the related database administrator for the detailed JDBC driver usage.</li>
</ol>
</ul>
<p>Click <b>NEXT</b>. 
</p><p><br>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Select_the_deployment_size">Select the deployment size</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=T-5" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor" title="Edit section: ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;action=edit&amp;section=T-5" title="Edit section: ">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>On the <b>Deployment size</b> page, select a deployment size, and then click <b>NEXT</b>.
</p><p><br>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Configure_the_connection">Configure the connection</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=T-6" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor" title="Edit section: ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;action=edit&amp;section=T-6" title="Edit section: ">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ol>
<li>On the <b>Connection</b> page, enter the external access hostname and port that you will use to access the suite user interface.
<ul>
<li>For an installation with only one master node, the external hostname and port fields are automatically filled. By default, the external hostname is the hostname of the first master node.</li>
<li>For an installation with more than one master node enter a fully-qualified domain name (FQDN) that is resolved to the virtual IP address of the external hostname. Provide the host names based on the following criteria:
<a class="buttonfullscr" onclick="javascript:loadingTableButton(this);"><button class="flscrbtn"><i class="material-icons flscricn">open_in_new</i><div style="margin: auto 5px;">View Fullscreen</div></button></a><table>
<tbody><tr>
<th>Configuration of master nodes
</th>
<th>Corresponding value in install.properties
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td>Master nodes in the same subnet
</td>
<td>Hostname must resolve to the value specified in HA_VIRTUAL_IP parameter
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>Master nodes are in different subnets
</td>
<td>Hostname must resolve to the value specified in LOAD_BALANCER_HOST parameter
</td></tr></tbody></table></li>
</ul></li>
<li>To use custom certificates, select <b>Use custom certificates</b>. You get additional options to choose the certificate format. When using custom certificates, you must import the Certification Authority (CA) certificates into the browser from where you will log on to the management portal.</li>
<li>Choose a certificate format.
<ul>
<li>If you choose the <b>PKCS#1 or PKCS#8</b> option:
<ol>
<li>Select a <b>CA certificate</b>. This is a root certificate.</li>
<li>Select a <b>Server certificate</b>. The supported certificate formats are: .crt, .cer, and .pem file.</li>
<li>Select a key file. The supported private key formats are <code>PKCS1</code> and <code>PKCS8</code>.</li>
<li>Enter the private key password for the encrypted private key file.</li>
<ul>
<li>The root certificate is the only root certificate that must be trusted and from the parent domain.</li>
<li>The server certificate must be a certificate chain. It must contain the origin server certificate (server.crt) and all intermediate certificates. The root certificate/CA is optional for the server certificate.</li>
<li>The server certificate must be in the following sequence: the original server certificate, the intermediate certificated and the root certificate. Merge all the certificates into a certificate chain.</li>
</ul>
</ol></li>
<ul><li>If you choose the <b>PKCS#12</b> option:
<ol>
<li>Choose a CA .crt file for CA certificate.</li>
<li>Select a .pfx file for the PKCS#12 file.</li>
<li>Enter the PKCS#12 file password.</li>
<li>Enter the private key password.</li>
</ol></li>
<p>If you did not specify the private key password, the CDF installer will use the PKCS#12 file password as key password. 
</p>
</ul>
You can also update the certificates on the management portal after the installation.
<li>Click <b>NEXT</b>.   </li>
</ul></li></ol>
<p><br>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Add_master_nodes">Add master nodes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=T-7" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor" title="Edit section: ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;action=edit&amp;section=T-7" title="Edit section: ">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ol>
<li>If you have specified a value for the <code>HA_VIRTUAL_IP</code> or <code>LOAD_BALANCER_HOST</code> parameter in the install.properties file, the <b>Master High Availability</b> page is displayed. To configure more than one master node, select the <b>Make master highly available</b> option. Otherwise, click <b>NEXT</b> to add worker nodes.  
</li>
<li>Provide the following information on the <b>Add Master Node</b> page:
<ol>
<li>Enter the host name or IPv4 address of the master node. You must use the same server name format for all cluster nodes: either host name or IP address. You can enter the default host name. The host name must resolve to an IPv4 address. If it is resolved to both an IPv4 address and an IPv6 address, delete the resolved IPv6 address. Click <b>Ignore warning</b> to ignore the host checking errors.</li>
<li>Enter a user name. This must be the root user or a sudo user with the correct installation permission.</li>
<li>Choose the verification mode as Password or Key-based and then enter your password or upload a private key file respectively. If you choose Key-based, you must first enter a username and then upload a private key file when connecting the node with a private key file. </li>
<li>Enter the ThinPool Device path. Specify the path that you configured for the master node. For example: <code>/dev/mapper/docker-thinpool</code>. You must have already set up the Docker thin pool for all cluster nodes that need to use thin pools. This is an optional step.</li>
<li>Enter the Flannel IFace value if the master node has more than one network adapter. This must be a single IPv4 address or name of the interface for Docker inter-host communication. This is an optional step.</li>
<li>Click <b>Save</b>. The installer performs a system check before adding the master node. If an error occurs, the master node configuration is not saved.</li>
</ol></li>
<li>Repeat the steps above to add the third master node.</li>
<li>Click <b>NEXT</b>. </li>
</ol>
<p><br>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Add_worker_nodes">Add worker nodes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=T-8" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor" title="Edit section: ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;action=edit&amp;section=T-8" title="Edit section: ">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ol>
<li>On the <b>Worker Nodes configuration</b> page, select the <b>Allow suite workload to be deployed on the master node</b> option to deploy the workload on the master node (we recommend this option only for test environments and not for production environments). Otherwise, click <b>Add</b>. The <b>Worker Node Detail</b> window is displayed.
<ol>
<li>Choose the required type. Currently, only <b>Standard</b> is available.</li>
<li>Enter the FQDN or IPv4 address of a worker node. You must use the same server name format for all cluster nodes: either host name or IP address. The host name must resolve to an IPv4 address. If it is resolved to both an IPv4 address and an IPv6 address, delete the resolved IPv6 address. If you use a customized host name, the host name must follow one of the hostname rules defined in Host Naming Rules and RFC Documents. </li>
<li>Type the User Name. This must be the root user or a sudo user with the correct installation permission.</li>
<li>Choose a verification mode as Password or Key-based, and then enter your password or upload a private key file. If you are using a key-based authentication, you must first enter a user name and then upload a private key file when connecting the node with a private key file.</li>
<li>Type the ThinPool Device path. For example, <code>/dev/mapper/docker-thinpool</code>.</li>
<li>Type the Flannel IFace value if the worker node has more than one network adapter.</li>
<li>Ensure that the <b>Skip resource check</b> option is clear. The best practice is to not skip resource checking.</li>
<li>Click <b>Save</b>.</li>
<li>Repeat the steps above to add more worker nodes.</li>
</ol></li>
<li>Click <b>NEXT</b>.  </li>
</ol>
<p>Make sure you do not delete any pod while you are adding master nodes and worker nodes or installing the suite, even when the pod status  is "Completed".<br>
For example, you must not delete any pod similar as below:<br>
</p>
<pre>NAMESPACE    NAME                                        READY  STATUS            RESTARTS   AGE    IP             NODE                  NOMINATED NODE   READINESS GATES
core         cdf-add-node-1555502049787                  0/1     Completed         0         8h      192.16.0.1       master1.mycompany.com      &lt;none&gt;          &lt;none&gt;
</pre>
<p>After the installation , if you use command <code>kubectl delete pod &lt;pod name&gt; </code> to delete  the pods in “Completed” status, all the historical logging information associated with the execution of this pod will be deleted as well.
</p><p><br>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Configure_file_storage">Configure file storage</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=T-9" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor" title="Edit section: ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=ITOM_Container_Deployment_Foundation:2019.02/SelectDeploymentConfiguration&amp;action=edit&amp;section=T-9" title="Edit section: ">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>On the <b>File Storage</b> page, a list of NFS volumes required for the CDF and suite installation is displayed. Before you proceed, make sure that you have already configured the required NFS shares for CDF and the suite, and the exported NFS folders are empty. <br>
Perform the following steps for each NFS volume. 
</p>
<ol>
<li>
 Select one of the following file system types.

<ul>
<li>Self-Hosted NFS: A distributed file system that allows a client to access the files on the remote server over a network like local</li> storage. In this case, the installer will check for the available mount points mount the shared remote directory to a local directory.
<li>Managed NFS: A remote file system such as EFS, NetApp, etc. In this case, the installer will mount the shared remote directory to a local directory.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Enter the NFS server host name or IP address. You must use the same server name format for all the volumes: either host name or IP address.</li>
<li>Select the NFS volume from the dropdown list, and then click <b>Validate</b>. If you have selected the internal PostgreSQL as the database, there will be an additional NFS volume listed. Select both the volumes. You can also type the exported path by clicking the arrow icon on the exported path row. 
</li>
<li>Choose the exported path for <b>itom-logging-vol</b> to mount the log volume to NFS. <br><br>If you have previously configured the exported volumes (for example, if you are resuming a paused installation or performing a re-installation), you only need to configure the <code>db-backup-vol</code> volume again.
<ul><li>The <b>db-node1-vol</b> and <b>db_node2-vol</b> volumes are available only if you selected the out-of-the-box PostgreSQL database for CDF and selected the <b>PostgreSQL High Availability</b> option. The <b>db-single-vol</b> volume appears on this page instead if you specified an external PostgreSQL database for CDF, or if you selected the <b>Out-of-the-box</b> CDF PostgreSQL database without selecting the <b>PostgreSQL High Availability</b> option.</li>
<li><i>itom-vol-claim</i>: This volume is for the CDF core namespace.</li>
<li><i>db-backup-vol</i>: This volume is for the CDF database backup.</li>
<li><i>itom-logging-vol</i>: This volume is for the aggregated log volume. Configure this volume to the exported shared NFS volume for logs.</li></ul>
</li>
<li>After you have configured all the NFS volumes, Click <b>NEXT</b>. A warning is displayed.  </li>
<li>Click <b>Yes</b> to start deploying the master and worker nodes.</li>
</ol>
<p>After you click <b>Yes</b>, you cannot go back to the Select phase. 
</p>
